<subSubSection id="41F9A877CA61F68187B23128F0C8D8A3" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="52C0B00060D66CB4BDC4D2371F9B07BE" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="73600AF6F458D9718A946830E1C984FE" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
A very characteristic but relatively rare otolith putatively related to 
<taxonomicName id="AA9FB7E95D2650226667F7FA56E7FD5A" genus="D." lsidName="D. epipedus" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="epipedus">
<emphasis id="72827BB85FCCE188AAC63BC73E35E8D3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">D. epipedus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see above for distinction) that has thus far only been recorded from the late Burdigalian to Langhian of Europe (stratigraphically younger references in 
<bibRefCitation id="DDA237F57D79EE0FD8097797E13D3B75" author="Brzobohaty ́, R" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin de l'Institut Royal des Sciences Naturelles de Belgique, Sciences de la Terre" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="185 - 206" refId="B9" refString="Brzobohatý, R, Nolf, D, 2000. Diaphus otoliths from the European Neogene (Myctophidae, Teleostei). Bulletin de l'Institut Royal des Sciences Naturelles de Belgique, Sciences de la Terre 70: 185 - 206" title="Diaphus otoliths from the European Neogene (Myctophidae, Teleostei)." volume="70" year="2000">Brzobohatý and Nolf 2000</bibRefCitation>
, need verification); however, the records from Japan document a much wider geographical distribution in the northern hemisphere. The systematic positions of both species must be regarded as tentative because they do not clearly align with any of the extant 
<taxonomicName id="574F2CED61646EF8AA41646478394B9E" class="Actinopterygii" family="Myctophidae" genus="Diaphus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Diaphus" order="Myctophiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="919893F43C1D143F52B4DA5789D2516F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Diaphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
otolith-based groups.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E1758A8C1441D73B37F83C40C8931527" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
<emphasis id="35F4B23EA8C4B323AA767F70E828DC13" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
<taxonomicName id="12830E9523295261DCE95CE949594FF9" baseAuthorityName="Brauer" baseAuthorityYear="1904" class="Actinopterygii" family="Myctophidae" genus="Diaphus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Diaphus splendidus" order="Myctophiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="splendidus">
<emphasis id="7AEEC9ECD6511BB6EDD71A96E0986555" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Diaphus splendidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Otolith Group after 
<bibRefCitation id="C1F2DE35017DA4868EDBB121306C58CC" author="Schwarzhans, W" journalOrPublisher="Palaeo Ichthyologica" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="41 - 82" refId="B58" refString="Schwarzhans, W, 2013a. A comparative morphological study of the Recent otoliths of the genera Diaphus, Idiolychnus and Lobianchia (Myctophidae). Palaeo Ichthyologica 13: 41 - 82" title="A comparative morphological study of the Recent otoliths of the genera Diaphus, Idiolychnus and Lobianchia (Myctophidae)." volume="13" year="2013 a">Schwarzhans (2013a)</bibRefCitation>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
